    "response_text": "The mean household initial risk attitude remains constant at approximately 0.0074 throughout the 100-year simulation period. This temporal stability reflects the fixed nature of initial risk dispositions, which serve as static reference points for how farmers perceive uncertainty when evaluating pasture conditions and determining deviations from recommended livestock numbers.\n\nThe metric exhibits zero variance and no significant trends across any observation window, indicating that the population-level baseline risk attitude does not drift or fluctuate over time. Individual households maintain their specific initial risk values—whether negative, neutral, or positive—throughout all simulation years, as these attitudes represent inherent characteristics assigned at initialization rather than learned or adapted behaviors. This constancy persists regardless of the distinct learning strategies employed by different household groups, confirming that initial risk dispositions remain unchanged even as farmers accumulate experience or observe neighbors over the century-long simulation."  
}

